<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     5. KEY THINGS TO KNOW (Tabs)
═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="cd-tabs">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Key Things to Know</h2>
    <div class="cd-tabs__wrap">
      <div class="cd-tabs__nav">
        <button class="tab-btn active" data-tab="1">Relational Databases<i class="fas fa-chevron-right tab-arrow"></i></button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="2">NoSQL & Document Stores<i class="fas fa-chevron-right tab-arrow"></i></button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="3">Performance & Indexing<i class="fas fa-chevron-right tab-arrow"></i></button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="4">Data Security & Compliance<i class="fas fa-chevron-right tab-arrow"></i></button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="5">Backup & Disaster Recovery<i class="fas fa-chevron-right tab-arrow"></i></button>
      </div>
      <div class="cd-tabs__content">
        <div class="tab-panel active" data-panel="1">
          <p>Relational databases like PostgreSQL and MySQL remain the gold standard for transactional data where consistency and integrity are non-negotiable. ACID compliance, foreign key constraints, and mature tooling make them ideal for financial systems, ERP platforms, and any application where data correctness comes first.</p><p>The Demski Group designs schemas that balance normalization with practical query performance, using views, stored procedures, and materialized query tables strategically to keep your application fast without sacrificing data quality.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tab-panel" data-panel="2">
          <p>NoSQL databases — including MongoDB, DynamoDB, and Cassandra — shine in use cases requiring flexible schemas, horizontal scalability, or extremely high write throughput. They're excellent choices for user-generated content, real-time analytics, and event-driven architectures where a rigid relational model would create bottlenecks.</p><p>The Demski Group evaluates your access patterns, data volume, and consistency requirements to determine whether NoSQL is right for you — or whether a polyglot persistence approach using both SQL and NoSQL gives you the best of both worlds.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tab-panel" data-panel="3">
          <p>Database performance problems compound over time as data volumes grow. The Demski Group conducts thorough query analysis using EXPLAIN plans, slow query logs, and profiling tools to identify the exact bottlenecks causing latency in your system.</p><p>Our optimizations range from simple index additions to full query rewrites, partition strategies, connection pool tuning, and the introduction of read replicas or caching layers — all calibrated to deliver measurable improvements without disrupting your production environment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tab-panel" data-panel="4">
          <p>Databases hold your most sensitive assets: customer PII, financial records, health data. The Demski Group implements defense-in-depth security — network isolation, role-based access with least privilege, column-level encryption for sensitive fields, and comprehensive audit trails — to protect that data from both external threats and insider risks.</p><p>We're experienced with the compliance requirements of HIPAA, SOC 2 Type II, GDPR, and PCI-DSS, helping you pass audits and maintain the documentation trail that regulators and enterprise customers demand.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tab-panel" data-panel="5">
          <p>A database without a tested recovery plan is a liability. The Demski Group designs and implements automated backup strategies — point-in-time recovery, geo-redundant snapshots, and transaction log archiving — with recovery time objectives (RTO) and recovery point objectives (RPO) that match your business's tolerance for downtime and data loss.</p><p>We go beyond backups to document and rehearse full disaster recovery runbooks, so your team knows exactly what to do if the worst happens — and can restore service in minutes, not days.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

